{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514108"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12273"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12273"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.08,0.03,0.03,0.85]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77826"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4795"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12273"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"380"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"9385"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26748"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77826"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing numbness and tingling in the thumb, index, and long fingers of the left hand. The symptoms are worse at night and also during the day when he is driving his car. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is marked atrophy of the thenar eminence of his left hand (Image). The patient\u0027s symptoms are reproduced when the wrist is flexed for 60 seconds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely to be impacted?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Musculocutaneous nerve","Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve","Anterior interosseous nerve","Median nerve"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms and signs of carpal tunnel syndrome, which involves compression of the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E at the wrist. The characteristic distribution of symptoms in the thumb, index, and long fingers corresponds to the sensory distribution of the median nerve. The positive Phalen\u0027s test (wrist flexion) and thenar muscle atrophy are also typical findings in chronic cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies sensation to the little finger and ulnar half of the ring finger. Compression typically occurs at the elbow (cubital tunnel syndrome) and causes weakness of the intrinsic hand muscles but spares the thenar muscles. The pattern of sensory symptoms in this case does not match ulnar nerve distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies sensation to the dorsum of the hand and fingers. Compression typically occurs in the spiral groove of the humerus and presents with wrist drop and sensory changes on the dorsum of the hand, not the palmar aspect of the digits as described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies motor function to the biceps and brachialis muscles and provides sensory innervation to the lateral forearm only. It does not supply the hand and could not cause the described symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior interosseous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a pure motor branch of the median nerve that supplies the flexor pollicis longus, flexor digitorum profundus (radial half), and pronator quadratus. It has no sensory function and therefore could not cause the sensory symptoms described.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carpal tunnel syndrome presents with sensory symptoms in the distribution of the median nerve (thumb, index, and long fingers)","Phalen\u0027s test (wrist flexion) reproduces symptoms of carpal tunnel syndrome","Chronic median nerve compression leads to thenar muscle atrophy"],"references":["Duvuru G, Stone JH, Imboden JB, Hellmann DB. Current diagnosis and treatment. Rheumatology.","Sevy JO, Sina RE, Varacallo MA. Carpal Tunnel Syndrome. 2023 Oct 29. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28846321. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28846321/","Genova A, Dix O, Saefan A, Thakur M, Hassan A. Carpal Tunnel Syndrome: A Review of Literature. Cureus. 2020 Mar 19;12(3):e7333. doi: 10.7759/cureus.7333. PMID: 32313774; PMCID: PMC7164699. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32313774/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12273"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18313"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18313"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e79fe985-f682-4bae-9a28-a74931aa6c05.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e79fe985-f682-4bae-9a28-a74931aa6c05.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":540}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63347"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-